Energy harvesting from human body heat depends on the temperature change of the body and involves two types of mechanisms: the thermoelectric generators (TEGs) and the pyroelectric generators (PEGs). TEG is developed on the principle of thermoelectric conversion and converts the temperature difference across the device into an electrical signal [101], whereas PEG relies on the temporal temperature variations of the device. TEG is a thermocouple made of two different conductors in which two junctions are maintained at high temperature Th\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
